Never many people, on weekends usually 2-3 parent w couple kids avg at most. No 5 star only because there's no bathrooms. 4-5 picnic tables & couple benches. Does have own little parking lot too.<//text>

As I was working in the radio I forgot that I removed the screws that hold the amplifier in the faring.  Well, the dang amplifier slid out and bounced off my front fender leaving a dent.  I was devastated.  My bike is flawless despite putting lots of mileage on it.  As I said earlier I take good care of her.

I immediately searched Google for dent repair.  This is how I found Mauricio "Dentman" Ca√±as.  I called him and he was very professional and knowledgeable.  He asked for pictures which I sent him.  Mauricio told me he might be able to help me.  Despite already having work for the day, he made time to meet with me same day.

I met Mauricio and he took a look at my bike.  He handed me a heat gun and showed me where to point it.  I listened to him as he grabbed another tool and began to manipulate the fender of my motorcycle with the tool.  About 30 seconds later the dent was completely gone.  I was in shock.  My bike was back to her flawless self.

Then Mauricio shocked me again.  He told me how much he was charging me.  I couldn't believe it.  If I took my bike to a shop it would cost me 5-6 times what he charged me.  If I bought a new fender, shoot, I don't even want to think about that.

<Text>Cottage Dental people (mostly attractive women) helped me come to a decision about ripping out an old gold crown and replacing it with a new ceramic crown. <gmapID>0x80dcd5e8a0e19721:0xde812927d79c744a</gmapID>< review>
I won't scare you with my horror stories from my past dentists, but I can tell you that I would have preferred to pull all my teeth out before setting foot in another dentist office again. If it wasn't for Yelp, I wouldn't have found Cottage Dental/Kid's Corner Dental and I probably would've had dentures by the time I turned 40. That's how badly I hated the dentist.

I ended up caving in when I had some bad coffee stains on my front teeth and it got to the point where I wasn't smiling anymore. I just knew I was going to go in and they were going to tell me I needed a deep cleaning, root canals, bridges, bleaching, and probably braces (because everyone knows how much a normal dentist tries to upsell you on everything). I was dreading it. So I turned to Yelp and found Cottage Dental. Cottage Dental is located on Chapman Abenue in Fullerton, but I needed to make a Saturday appointment so they scheduled me at their Kid's Corner office, which is on Bastanchury and Brea in Fullerton. From the minute I walked in, I knew it was going to be a good experience. Stephanie, who works the front desk, was friendly and listened to my horror stories and suffered through my anxiety-riddled rant about dentists. She quickly put me at ease and didn't make me feel like I was a horrible person because I hadn't gone to the dentist in 6 years. The staff is so amazingly friendly, you just feel instantly at ease as soon as you get in the chair. I was still nervous about what I would need and I couldn't believe it when they told me a regular cleaning would get rid of the stains, a deep cleaning was not needed, as long as I came back after 4 months instead of 6, and I only had two cavities. Not only did they not upsell me, they worked with me on a payment plan that most dentists would never dream of doing. It's not Care Credit either, although they do offer that. It's their own payment plan and it's honestly really affordable. They don't make you feel like you have to do all the work in one sitting either. They schedule you months in advance and allow you to financially plan for the work you need.

I could go on and on and on, but I will say that my kids actually LOOK FORWARD to going to the dentist now, I have been vigilant about going every six months for the past 5 years, and I have referred at least 10 different people to them. I can't say enough good things and I wish I could give them 10 stars!

THANK YOU COTTAGE DENTAL/KID'S CORNER!!!</review>

<rate>4<//rate>< text>
Went here because cannery was way too crowded, and this place is honestly underrated. This place is really good and pretty cheap, but the service can be slow because there is only one waitress, which I didn't mind at all. It's a very small location near a liqupr store, and is actually clean on the inside even though the outside looks sorta sketch. I had the waffle combo, and honestly the waffles here are really, really, REALLY good. I ate it with the bacon from my meal to make that salty and sweet combo which I kind of like. They have a new waffle maker (waitress told me), so they're coming out super fluffy, but sort of dense at the same time, and slightly crispy. Bf had the hills special, which he said was really good and filling.<//text>

1450545296382< /Time>
< rating>
4< /rating>
< Text>
Little breakfast place totally worth dropping in on. I had French toast, eggs, bacon, and sausage. He had a bacon and cheese omelet with hashbrowns, and toast. The French toast was crispy on the edges and absorbed all the syrup without falling apart. They serve it with a *lot* of butter and powdered sugar so take note. The actually know how to make eggs over-medium. The omelet was hearty, the hashbrowns were lightly browned. They are a Coke house (yay!) $23 before tip.
Good solid breakfast food in large portions, friendly staff, quick service, inexpensive, and you can get a table at 11am on a Sunday.</Text>

< Review>
I been going here faithfully for over 20 years, the crew are always the most knowledgeable and experienced you will meet within a 10 mile radius. They can figure what parts you need just by telling them how the car is behaving.  They are always polite. Even when a customer isn't.  You can tell they love their job. And they always have the right OEM  rated parts. And it never takes more than a day to get any specialty part if needed.
I believe in " You get what you pay for" and "A  nickel saved is a nickel earned".
NAPA, Auto parts is a blend of both of those quotes.<//Review>

< Text>
Please be aware, double check your purchases!! I was visiting Newport and I bought a dolce and Gabbana perfume from this location that looked sealed up and had a security tag on as well. So I didn't double check it when I was paying for it. Later when I opened the packet, I noticed the cap was missing and the whole bottle was empty!! I called the shop and explained the situation and told them that I cannot return it to the store because I was on my way back home. The manager told me to take it to any ulta store and get a refund or return. I did that but was told that they won't return or exchange it since it was not bought at their store. I called the store back and told them the situation and explained to them what had happened but they said they couldn't do anything about it because it had never happened before and they checked the security camera and said they didn't see anyone temper with it before they rung me up. Keep in mind, this tempering could have happened prior to me buying it and I suspect its one of their staff who's doing this!! Im really disappointed with this kind of service. Even customer service told me they couldn't do anything about this and that i would have to go to the store i bought it from. I even asked if my sister could bring in the item with the receipt if i mailed it to her and they said they cannot do that. Just be careful purchasing items from ANY ulta store and especially this store where they are covering up this kind of activity where they temper with the item and put it back on the shelf.
Looks like someone carefully opened the packet and glued it back. The glued part has fingerprints on it as well!! So I can guarantee that one of the staff did this!

<resp>None</resp><Time>1550898674895</Time><Text>Italian/Argentinian food, family owned, good service and nice workers. High quality, simple, very tasty food. The salads are crisp and fresh, and I love the dressings; their Italian is amazing trust me try it, and my family goes for their blue cheese, or you can go with their other options or a simple oil and balsamic. I think they have a few salad options, but I just love their simple green salad. The burgers are enormous and made with very high quality meat, good luck finishing that beast of a burger. The fries and big, a generous portion, crispy outside and moist inside (tip: they come unsalted so add salt as soon as they come, and beware on first bite, they're steaming hot inside). The sausage is amazing. Their steaks are perfectly seasoned and grilled perfectly every time I've ordered, with the best chimichurri. And the chicken, it's so well seasoned, high quality, and always cooked perfectly, always juicy on the inside. I even love their potatoes, so simple but really good. I've never had anything here I didn't like. They also serve wine. And every meal comes with a bread basket of amazing bread, but save room for the dinner. Tip: Mara's bakery up the block is our go to for dessert after, or Classico by the park. Enjoy!</Text></record>

< Text>
My wife and I came here on a mini honeymoon and had a great experience! The room rates were great probably due to COVID. The hotel was very clean and had hand sanitizers inside and outside of the elevators. The room felt very clean which was our main concern right now. Unfortunately the restaurant and bar was closed because of COVID but there‚Äôs a decent amount of food options nearby. If you plan on parking, I recommend booking the parking package online when you book the room to save a little bit.

Everyone at this hotel from the valet guys to the front desk was incredible! We opted for no housekeeping to keep it safe but every time we called the front desk to change out our garbage and bring more espresso, they were on top of it! Espy at the front desk was beyond nice! She definitely made our experience great! She would even call the room to make sure that they brought extra towels or espresso for us. Thank you to everyone at the W! We‚Äôll definitely be back whenever we‚Äôre in SF!<//Text>

< Text>
I have been to San Francisco countless times and have stayed at luxury hotels that did not offer the level of customer service that I received at the W. It made my girlfriend's first visit to San Francisco extremely memorable.

From check in to check out, parking to eating, everything was exceptional. 

The location is perfect. Not crowded with tourists (like me) and the perfect atmosphere for meeting friends and new friends downstairs in the lobby bar area. 

The W is an easy walk to the convention center, Union Square, Embarcadero, restaurants, and the highway. 

I would highly recommend staying at the W San Francisco.< /Text>

<user_name>Celeste Peterson< /user_name><Time>1578464862697< /Time>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< text>
It's been a while since I last stayed at the W in San Francisco, which I have avoided because of the loud party clientele they have had in the past and pricey pet fee (we usually have our dogs with us in San Francisco) but this time we were there overnight for a wedding and I was quite comfortable and happy.
The location is great, right in the SOMA next to SF MoMA, the Yerba Buena Gardens, and SF Convention Center.
Our room faced a brick wall, but I appreciated its privacy and quiet. The bed was super comfortable, and I absolutely loved that they carried Davines products. Room service was tasty and quickly delivered.
I think the worst part of the stay is actually the staff - don't get me wrong, they make every attempt to make you feel welcomed and comfortable, but they themselves don't seem happy or comfortable and that comes across when they interact with guests. It's just a bit ingenuine and... stiff. That said, I'd rather have a slightly awkward staff than a rude one - so I'll take it!
In any case, The W will soon need a decorative update but right now the place is clean and comfortable.</text>

< review>
My siblings and I met in SF for one night because my little brother was recently dumped by his girlfriend of 6 years. Before our stay I received an email from Vanessa asking if there was anything I needed prior to my arrival. I requested two things, early check if possible and a list of things we could do in one night considering my little sister was a minor. She promptly responded saying she would do her best to make sure our room was available when we got there and she sent a list of things near by we could do in one day! During check-in we were greeted by Arleigh! She was exceptional and quick. She asked why we were there and we told her. She later sent  a bottle of bubbly to our room which really made my little brother's day. Good job W, not only was the service amazing, but the property was sexy, fun and we had an amazing view in our room. We would book again for sure! Good Job!<//review>

< review>
Just go book a room now. Simply awesome. The bed in my room was the most comfortable bed I've ever slept in.  I slept so well, I could have slept through the apocalypse.

I was in town for work and was looking forward to my first stay in San Fran. I got a room high up and loved the views. The rooms were designed in a trendy but modern way.

One night I got back late from my shoot that day. I ordered in and got the salad that has chicken and avocado on it. The thing was huge. I did not expect that since it was not expensive at all. Very delicious.

All in all a great stay. I appreciated that they had all manner of snacks and drinks in the mini bar area of the room. I chuckled when I noticed they even include a little pleasure kit you can buy. You might be thinking "yuck", but come on, who hasn't had a little fun in a hotel room. Kinda the point right?</review>

I use hotel rooms for work, including sitting at a desk and using my laptop. The room had an elevated desk and an uncomfortable chair.... terrible for working. 

Also, I like to unpack my things. This room had a total of one drawer available. The "nightstands" were small, cheesy plastic pedestals with no storage. The whole room feels like it is designed to make cleaning easier.

I would not stay here again for work or pleasure.< /Review>

I was a guest at the W on 3rd in San Fran for two nights this week. The hotel was lovely, and room was great. But I cannot say thank you enough to Brian and Clay at the bar. < Text>
I decided to book a room at the W because when I lived in Austin the W out there was really nice, and comfortable. This location in San Francisco is also in a really good location and near a lot of shopping and food, and the staff is really incredible. I also love the design of the interior, and Trace has some great food. On the other hand, there are some things about this hotel that make me want to stay away from ever coming back. The biggest reason I say that is because the bed was hard as a rock. I sleep on a very firm mattress, but this thing didn't even feel like a mattress. It was like sleeping on the ground, but more disappointing considering you paid to sleep on this thing. Also there overnight parking was I think $65, which is absurd. If it wasn't for the incredibly overpriced parking and the embarrassingly bad bed, this review would be completely different. There is a lot of potential to have a nice comfortable stay here, but the one thing that you're supposed to relax on is worse than a bed at Motel 6.<//Text>

<gmapID>0x8085807d77b62311:0x84055e3c40a911eb< /gmapID>< review>
I've stayed at many of the Starwood properties in San Francisco. If you are looking for a cool hip trendy fun hotel - then you can't beat the W Hotel.

I stayed in a Mega Corner which had a great view of the city. Room was very comfortable and had a nice layout. 

Staff was very attentive. Cesar was especially helpful and accommodating. 

Great overall Platinum recognition. 

Platinum benefit of free breakfast was the most flexible I've seen at any hotel. Most hotels require you to eat breakfast before 10:30/11am. Here you can eat up to 2 pm (on Sunday, and Saturday?) breakfast/brunch. Also there were 3 different options to select and if you didn't like those then you could get a $15/person credit towards whatever you like from the menu. I appreciate when the hotel does little things like this to make their guests happy. 

I will absolutely be back!</review>

We just had out wedding here over the weekend and I have to say, it was perfect! Lindsay is absolutely amazing and helped us with every last detail from the day we contacted her 15 months ago until the last hour of the wedding, all while being super fun, hilarious, and bubbly. The rest of the staff including Dave were also fantastic, and were able to make everything I wanted happen and more.

The newly renovated 4th floor terrace is absolutely stunning! It's ultra modern with its edgy architecture, huge chandelier/skylight that extends the length of the room, built in up lighting on every wall, and a full length window wall that you can fully open to reveal the amazing view of the cityscape.

The food was wonderful, I've never had better crab cakes, filet mignon, wedge salad, etc. anywhere else.

We had the privilege of staying in one of their amazing corner suites that overlooked the entire west side of the city.

Our guests were completely floored by how amazing our venue was. I still can't believe how perfect our wedding was and I can't thank Lindsay and her staff enough for pulling out all the stops and making us feel like $1MM for our day.

I highly recommend the W for weddings. If you want the perfect wedding, with new, modern, unique venue, a fantastic coordinator, amazing food, and to be treated like royalty for your entire stay, you need to have it here. You will not be disappointed.</Text>

< review>
Recently stayed in this hotel on a business trip for two weeks. The W is centrally located in the SOMA neighborhood near the Moscone conference center, many great restaurants, and a short walk from the BART station. It is a newer building with modern decor and fits the bill as a "W" hotel - fun, young, hip, etc. with,24-hour room service,24-hour gym with modern equipment

The staff were very friendly - at check-in and at the lobby-level bar. The room was very spacious, comfortable, and had an excellent view (I had a 22nd floor room). My bed/linens were clean and very comfortable. I had a very comfortable stay and I would definitely return.<//review>

< text>
Stayed here after 3 nights in Fisherman‚Äôs Wharf Sheraton. What a difference, this hotel oozes class and atmosphere. Located next door to SOMA and a nice stroll to St Martins Square. Our Fabulous Double Room was small but extremely well appointed. A Nespresso coffee machine, full mini bar, cocktail mix set - lovely Bliss amenities in the bathroom which by the way has a full size bath! The beds were like any other W bed - extremely comfortable, the room was sound proof and the airconditioning spot on. Breakfast was included in our rate, it was refreshing to have an alacarte option for this and a breakfast device that finished at a very civilised 2pm!
It was dissapointing that the Bliss Spa was closed for renovations and that the pool had been replaced with a gym.
Service in the hotel was phenomenal- staff were always attentive accomodating and most importantly genuine!< /text>

There's not enough parking so when we arrived, their valet was full and we had to scramble to find parking in a public lot. <Rating>None</Rating>< Text>
This hotel was nice.I was a little concerned on reading some negative reviews. The staff were OK, not overly nice as perhaps they could be for the class of hotel, but perhaps the area is not none for great service. The beds were lovely of course. We had two rooms, and they were able to get us right next to eachother, with a nice view of the bay bridge. one thing, one of the rooms was missing some of the decor elements - throw pillows for window set and color pop decorative blanket at end of bed. These were really important since the room is otherwise minimalist with little color. I recommend to the hotel that each room remains decorated as the designer intented. On a final note, the spa was great. The signature Bliss 75 massage with parafin foot treatment was spectacular.< /Text>

<Text>Your typical, hip and trendy W property in a good location just south of Market. Bar scene VERY cool and sheik. Staff at reception quite friendly and service was good. The rooms are a bit small but I had a good view so no complaints. Bed was a bit soft as I prefer a firmer mattress. Perhaps mattress needed replacing.Also, of the 4 pillows, only ONE pillow was down/feather and my preference is documented on file as "down or feather." Not a huge big deal, but nevertheless a slight subtraction here with respect to housekeeping.

Bathroom quite small but nicely appointed. Weak water pressure, and would have liked a shower with more pressure. But overall it was a nicely appointed and comfortable room, with excellent staff attitude. I'd recommend for sure, and would give it 4.25 stars if I could. < review>
I arrived at 2:30 hoping I might be able to get into my room a little before the 3pm check in to nap and have more time to get ready before a long evening out. I was told the room would be ready in 30-45 minutes and that I would receive a call when the room was ready. I waited 40 minutes before approaching the desk and was informed that the room would not be ready for anther 30-45 minutes. I was told I could have a room immediately if I were willing to accept a lower, construction facing view. I asked the staff member if it would be worth the wait and she intimated that I would have a much better view of the city on a higher floor. I decided to wait and stalked off into the city having already sat in the hotel bar for the better part of an hour. I didn't receive a phone call telling me my room was ready for a full hour and 20 minutes, double the quoted time. When I finally got into my room the view I had waited for was the windowless brown facade of an adjacent building. If I leaned to one side I could catch a little bit of the city reflecting off of it. Fully obstructed view. I was now running late, having waited triple the quoted time to enter my room and the better part of my afternoon was lost to the process. There was no acknowledgement of inconvenience save for a brief "sorry for the wait" from the second of three separate staff members I dealt with at check in.< /review>

There were no error messages or anything like that, so I hit submit a couple of more times to end up on the same page again with no confirmation that it actually submitted. I decided to wait it out and if it hadn't arrived in the morning I would call back. Apparently, two calls is a burden or something, at least that is how I was made to feel. Same guy answered the phone and put me through to the voicemail again before I even had a chance to tell him that it did not work yesterday. So I pressed "0" and had myself transferred back to him. <text>Overall, the hotel was good. I live local in the Bay Area but had a business function at the Metreon on Saturday in San Francisco so my partner and I decided to make a staycation weekend trip. The hotel lives up to the W brand and has a very hip and youthful vibe. Definitely reminds me of a Las Vegas atmosphere with the vibrant colors and music. The only area where I have a critique is check-in. We've stayed at Starwood properties in Portland, Seattle, Bellevue, Vancouver, Kauai, Maui, Oahu, and on the Big Island of Hawaii and each and every time I was recognized and thanked for being a loyal SPG member. This was the first time that didn't happen. The only reason I knew the gentleman assisting me knew I was an SPG member was that he asked if 12pm check-out was suitable. He also didn't ask if I needed assistance with any bags, nor explained any of the amenities the hotel had to offer. I know my stay was only for 1 night, but I would still have liked to know what amenities were available. Had I known there was no pool available at check-in, it would have saved us time searching through the brochures in the room and looking online and finally a call to the front desk to discover there was no pool on site. One of the highlights of our stay was ordering room service. The gentleman who set up our food in the room was excellent, much more attentive than the gentleman who checked us in. We ordered the dungeness mac and cheese, and a lamb pita sandwich and both were just outstanding! There were huge chunks of fresh dungeness crab and the lamb was perfectly cooked and not gamey at all. We had a corner room with a view of the city and it was quite large than what we were expecting. The room was very comfortable and we were able to get a good night's rest. Since there was no public parking available, we had to valet our car but the attendants there were also very friendly, attentive, and quick. The day we left, the valet attendant who brought our car also offered us bottled waters, which was a very nice and generous send off. We also brought our senior chihuahua with us since I know that the majority of Starwood properties are pet friendly. What I wasn't expecting was the $125 pet fee, considering that my chihuahua only weighed 3 pounds. I was just hoping that since my chihuahua was so tiny and that I have been a loyal SPG member and also a Westin vacation owner, that $125 fee could have been waived or reduced but overall I appreciate Starwood properties for being pet friendly.<//text>< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>

< text>
The hotel was incredibly noisy due to the strikers who were outside the entrance from the crack of dawn to late at night.
I was up charged to move to a quieter room, however, I could still hear the strikers at 6:30am in the morning!  Ouch
For some reason, this 4 star hotel did not have in room dining, which was inconvenient for me as I wanted to relax and dine in my room, which I was not able to do.  I was mistakenly charged $30 for a glass of $12 wine at the bar, which was a clumsy mistake and they did not seem particularly apologetic.  Overall, the room felt dated and the bed and pillows were not very comfortable.  I certainly wish I could have stayed somewhere else!<//text>

< review>
I've had the pleasure of staying at the W on several occasions. Today, was again no exception s Melanie was great at check-in the room amazing.

I would like to point out the reason I routinely stay at the W however. There is a manager named Vikram who is flat out spectacular. Several months back, my admin had scheduled my arrival for another week. I was in SF on one of the busiest convention weeks of the year with no room.

Vikram apologized (even though he and his amazing staff had nothing to do with the error) and then proceeded to call around and then PERSONALLY BOOK me a room at a competitor's hotel. Further, he called me once there to ensure I had arrived safe and that all is well.

You just don't see that level of customer service anymore and that is why I and my entire firm only stay at the W when in SF.

Thank you Vikram and amazing W staff!</review>

< Rate>
None</Rate>
< text>
The lobby lounge is beautiful and comfortable and offers a cozy space to unwind, which we desperately needed and availed ourselves of. We checked in a bit early, which turned out to be fine, and had a leisurely stay. Location is stellar - walking distance to excellent cafes. It'd be helpful if information like "what floor is the restaurant on" were listed anywhere in the hotel guide (it isn't - frustrating) and if coffee-making facilities are available, please just provide them rather than making the guest ask for them. My only other quibble is the entrance through the bar - loud disco music when arriving back after a tiring night, jarring - avoidable if you go around to the other entrance, but eh. Overall, the room was beautiful and comfortable, the hotel staff were breathtakingly helpful and kind (every single one of them!), we loved the lobby lounge in late afternoon and the food we had unwinding there was superb. It was a relief to relax and just trust that whatever we ordered would be fantastic, and that our waitress would take excellent care of us, and those things were true. There are lovely touches everywhere - the concierge desk had some refreshing lemonade and fresh apples available, loads of plugs on the desk in the room for charging up our various devices, the corner window seat/couch was cozy, the elevators are even decorated inside with scented oil and eye-catching 3-D artwork. There's a tiny bit of room for improvement, but this was an excellent place to be. Thank you!</text>

<user_id>None</user_id><username>AzMax</username><Time>1398902400000</Time><rate>None<//rate>< review>
I hate to write this because I am a very frequent guest at the SF W, love the people there, and have been treated royally over the years. Working in SF, it has been my home-away-from-home. As recently as a week ago, Claudia Nuta sent to my room a lovely cheese/cracker/nut tray after there had been a service mix up...greatly appreciated. But this week my stay, while fine overall, had a few bumps. First, the welcome desk computer at the W continues to list me as a Gold Starwood Preferred Member, not Platinum, which I am. A minor irritant, for sure, but I've asked to have this corrected repeatedly, without anything happening. I do prefer to be in a high-level floor with corner room to the right of the elevator, like -17 or -14 series. Not this time; I got 2803, which was fine, except I also had no tea service, as I request, the room telephone malfunctioned, and the TV remote control didn't work. I was able to get a replacement remote control so that I could operate the TV. On my 2nd day there, I ordered green tea and received it, and I did get my morning newspapers both days, per my hotel profile requests. So it was, as I noted, an okay visit overall, but this series of minor irritants made my stay somewhat less special than usual. I'm hoping it was an exception. I sincerely do hate to be a complainer because you folks have been great, but after 170 nights there +/- over the life of this hotel, I am spoiled and expect near perfection!< /review>

<user_id>None</user_id>< Text>
SPG status acknowledged - As a platinum member, I started by booking a standard room. They first upgraded me to a fabulous room, which I found too small. After a brief negotiation phone call, one of the manager managed to further upgrade us into a suite.
Cute decor - I love the window blinders and the sky blue decor throughout. Cute little cloud shaped mirrors add hints of fun.
City view - Of course you are going to have city views situated in the financial district. But the corner view room did amplify the grandness of SF City, especially with a top down view of Yerba Buena Park.
Some other random points:
- Convenient location
- Expensive valet parking
- B&O loudspeaker in suite living room</Text>

<username>Lynne2731</username><Time>1363046400000</Time><rate>None<//rate><Text>Let me count the ways this became my favorite San Francisco hotel:
1. I asked for Perrier in my room, and it was there when I arrived.
2. Restaurant and room service were fast and outstanding. Food much much much better than typical Starwood.
3. The beet salad and duck breast are not on the room service menu but they will make them for you -- and they are phenomenal. I ordered it two days in a row. And try the cookies!
4. Hotel provides a charging station by the bed that works for all phones! I didn't need my own charger. Great idea that should be in all rooms.
5. Staff goes out of the way to accommodate any needs. Allison in the restaurant was especially helpful. Thanks, Allison, for the treats.
6. It is convenient to the convention center (next door).

This is truly one of Starwood's best properties.< /Text><Pics>None</Pics><Response>None</Response>< gmap_id>

< Text>
I booked a prepaid rate in February, and upon check in I learned there was a cheaper rate but was not able to take advantage of the rate. I was told the rate I prepaid was a "very good rate", and that I had been upgraded to a corner room. Okay, if the rate I paid was more expensive than the current rate on day of check in, obviously my rate is not a "very good rate", and being upgraded comes with Platinum status of upgrade rooms are available. Not quite sure how either of the hotel staff reasonings were valid.

Upon check in, everyone was friendly and I had no issues with the front desk staff.

Once in my room, I noticed the following which in my opinion are unacceptable and show a lack of attention to detail. No cushion or pillows on the couch, what appeared to be toothpaste smeared in the bathroom water glasses, and the flat sheet used to cover the mattress was too small for the king size bed (I am thinking a queen size flat sheet was used). I contacted the front desk and they did bring up a cushion for the couch, replaced the water glasses in the room, and placed an appropriate size flat sheet overtop the mattress.

The next night, my partner and I decided to grab a sandwich and sit on the couch to eat prior to going out. We noticed what appeared to be dried vomit on the couch near the wall closer to the floor. I informed the front desk once again, and upon our return to the room I received a telephone message from the housekeeping manager letting me know he personally inspected the room and did not find any vomit on the wall by the couch. Clearly they got the placement of the vomit incorrect and if the manager truly did inspect the wall I would have hoped he would have seen the vomit on the couch too. It concerns me his attention to detail is not up to par.

Lastly, there was a feather on the floor outside our room which was not there upon check in but was there after the first instance occurred. Keep in mind the housekeeping manager came to the room to inspect the vomit situation and the feather was still on the floor outside our room. I would have expected the manager of all people the notice this detail and pick up the feather. The carpeting was a dark blue I believe and the feather was white. Not hard to miss in my opinion.

One thing I did not bother to inform the front desk about was the state of the window sills behind the shutters. I do not believe the sills have ever been cleaned. The amount of dust and dirt was repulsive, and I would hope this detail would not be overlooked.

I would not recommend this hotel, and do not plan on staying at this property again. As a matter of fact I planned to stay at the W in Hollywood later in the week and have since cancelled that reservation because of my first W experience in San Francisco.

I hope others have a better experience or find this review helpful.< /Text>

< review>
When booking this hotel via spg site there was not an indication of the construction that was happening around the hotel or at the property.
Due to this, the experience in Downtown San Francisco was very challenging. The make shift gym was in a small space covered with white tent. Condition was crammed, and very sub par to W/Starwood standards.
Construction around the property while it is out of your control, it would have been better to receive notice about this. At minimum recommend it being reflected in the room rates for guest.

The staff on site was very understanding to help accommodate a room change immediately. Our original room was very dark due and look directly into the construction zone. Fortunately staff helped improve our location which we appreciated very muhc.< /review>

< review>
The W is a very nice hotel, the spa, gym and pool are fantastic and the people are friendly and eager to help. I am unfortunately allergic to down feathers which are standard in making the beds in the W so comfortable. Three times I have stayed here and had to request the down on the bed to be changed out which I admit is a pain for everyone involved. The W is ill prepared to handle this request. There ARE poly fill pillows however they are in very short supply of any warm blankets or down alternative duvets or comforters. The first time I was told they were out of blankets and was offered an empty duvet cover, the second stay they seemed to handle this better and were able to substitute the feather bed with a blankets and swapped out the down duvet with poly fill- perfect! The third time, they swapped out the down for a thin and oddly sticky "blanket" material that they encased in the sheets which i had to double to be warm enough. The staff were all polite and efficient but management should consider better preparation for people who cannot sleep on down. In the meantime I will stick another starwood hotel. On a separe note the cable had odd spotty reception during two of my stays as well.<//review>

< Review>
Every time I've stayed at the W SF it's been fantastic! From the moment you step in the door, you're greeted with a friendly face and a willingness to meet every need. 1) Room 2612 is right by the hotel door that hides the service elevator and other doors. Starting at 6AM, it closed loudly continuously over and over, until we decided we should just get up. It was so loud that the first day I jumped out of bed thinking someone was coming into the room. I am a very deep sleeper so it's unusual for anything to wake me up. I talked to the front desk twice and they assured me that they were talking to everyone who uses that door to be considerate as well as to engineering to see if they could install a 'soft close'. We never heard back on this issue. On the second discussion, after four nights, they offered us another room. The issue is that we fully move into our room and that would of been a big undertaking that may or may not have been to a better room. You absolutely must solve this issue as it erodes the comfort of the room.

2) Air conditioner is set to go on / off by movement. We talked to front desk twice on this as well. The lady assured me that it would not go off when we were in the room. Well it does. < review>
I like this W, I really do. Via Platinum status, I've been spoiled over the past few years with some pretty sick upgrades (on a consistent basis). I didn't get much of an upgrade here, but that didn't stop me from seeing value in this property. I was also really disappointed that my Suite Night Awards didn't go through--as I saved them specifically for this stay.

Location: central to lots in SF proper. If you don't know the area well, this is a good point to base yourself (to be able to explore). Be sure to take advantage of the free Acura service (they take you TO, but not pick you up).

We were in a Cool Corner Room. Decent views. Impeccably clean. Great Asian-inspired design with some fun features. Was surprised to see a normal old school tub (no walk in shower). Comfy W bed. Cool seating area (invoking a Bay Window, I'm guessing?).

Great service, of course. We had bikes and they took care of them with no fuss (and for free). The Living Room is hip (and often hopping) (HA). Lots of OOONCE OOOONCE, especially on weekends and late nights.

As always, the Bliss products are heavenly.< /review>

< review>
I don't expect doors to be opened for me because I'm an ambassador member, but it would have been nice for the valet/door guys to pay attention when I walked up with my suitcase/backpack/bags in hand. I wasn't dressed in a suit like the rest of the customer base, so I was easily overlooked. This initial indication of how I could expect to be treated was irritating, especially after traveling from outside the continent.

I lowered my customer service expectations, but Ogy at the front desk turned this negative experience around. He didn't care that I was in running shoes, jeans and a hoody. He provided great customer service and is a great addition to the staff.
The excellent customer service continued at breakfast with Claudio (aka Champion). He was very friendly, and a pleasure to talk to.

The hotel is conveniently located just a short walk from the Montgomery BART station, which makes travel to/from the airports very cheap and easy. The Powell/Hyde street car stop is very close as well to see the downtown area.< /review>

<rating>None< /rating><Review>We came to town booking 2 rooms for 4 days to scatter the ashes of a loved one. The hotel was lively and fun, but certainly not loud or noticable in the rooms.

From check-in, we were welcomed warmly. The gentleman who checked us in helped us upgrade to rooms and moved us so that we were able to check in early. I came down with a question the next day, and he even remembered my name. That is service!

The restaurant and the bar were great, adn the girl who served us in the restaurant a few times at breakfast and once for dinner was very sweet and attentive.

We did book a "Bliss Spa" package that included credits at the spa. Unfortunatly, the spa was so busy the only thing we were able to book between the 2 of us over the 4 days was a single manicure. That left us with a significant credit. I inquired about it before checkout, at checkout, and the hotel followed up a day later as they tried to figure out what to do. I heard from one of the managers a little over a week later appologizing as it was a new package and they had not worked out the kinks yet. Instead of offering me SPG points, he simply refunded the complete value of the unused spa credits, and gave me SPG points on top of it, which was much more than I asked for to begin with.

It is clear that the staff care about their guests, and they all went above and beyond to make our stay enjoyable.

I will be back next year when I am back in San Francisco.</Review>< pics>

This is a facility that breaks from the brass, oak, marble ,traditional style luxury hotel. Black granite, stainless steel, and glass abound. With the addition of fresh lillies, fireplaces and modern seating areas

< user_name>
Patrick99</user_name>
<Date>1383091200000</Date><Rate>None< /Rate>< Text>
We were in town with some friends for a long weekend. We had booked 2 rooms, one was simply a high floor with an amazing view, although I would have appreciated a corner upgrade. The other room was upgraded to a suite, which was fantastic! The two bathrooms and showers made it so easy to get ready to go out at the same time.

The only negative with this was the fact that the suite was not ready until close to 5pm, nearly 2hrs after the promised time of 3pm, and when you arrive from the airport at 1pm, that's quite a long wait. Thankfully we were able to use the other room to change, cleanup, and store our bags. I brought this up to the hotel both during check-in and checkout, but also in an email and they did not seem to care or do anything about it.

My only other complaint was in regards to room service charging us for extra glasses, and then bringing the wrong ones. This however, was taken care of quite quickly.

The food in the restaurant, both for breakfasts and 1 dinner was amazing, and the cocktails were to die for. Definitely choose the breakfast as your Platinum amenity, as it gives you a deep discount, and it just may be the best breakfast in SF.

Upon checking out, I realized I had left my jacket in the suite closet. We had to check out of the suite early, as they refused us a late checkout (despite the fact that we had to check-in late). When we came back to check out of the other room and retrieve our things, they had retrieved the jacket for me, AND a phone charger we had left that I didn't even know about. That was wonderful and very good service. Thanks!

I will certainly be returning to this hotel and recommending it, and I just hope that they will learn to honor check-in times and if something happens and they cant, do something and don't refuse to honor a late check out!<//Text>

<Rating>None</Rating><text>Checked in early afternoon and ordered a steak sandwich from room service. Arrive promptly, but fries were obviously OLD and COLD, also the steak was chewy, undercooked, and I suspect also left over from a previous preparation.

<resp>None< /resp>< Text>
The hotel could definitely use some attention to detail & maintenance! I know the W hotel is meant to be modern etc. but this one is already looking a little dated, or perhaps it was cheaply done from the start. Sitting in the lounge my husband & I noticed torn pillow cases, random cords that could easily be concealed, & bits of trash & other unpleasing sites. Our room had a good amount of space & a little corner seating area which was nice. However the coffee table was all scuffed & there was extremely loud construction going on right next to our room. The amount of dust was actually disturbing! I'm not one to typically complain but I almost gagged when I saw the clumps of dust on the ipod dock. When I went to plug in my phone I again noticed so much collected dust on the cords & outlet I had to wipe it all down. The bed was comfortable & clean (from what I could tell). The spa menu & booklet w/ room service & hotel info was all wrinkled & written on from the previous guests. Walking in the hallway to the elevator from our room the exit sign was detached from the ceiling & in the elevators the doors were all scratched & dinged as if some rowdy guests were punching the metal doors. The pool was under construction during our stay as well. We chose this hotel for the last part of our honeymoon b/c of the location to restaurants we planned to visit & we were def. disappointed. Especially for $490/night! I would have had a better experience using AirBnB (which I will probably do in the future). The staff was nice & friendly which made it bearable.</Text>

< Text>
I have not previously been a fan of the W SF. Attitude, attitude, attitude. But I had to be in SF for five nights and this was the only hotel with the location I needed that had a room for all five nights available. So I booked it, unhappily. Things started as I was expecting: nobody at the front door to help with bags, couldn't find my reservation, no platinum recognition or upgrade. Same old, same old. However, over the five days I had a number of minor requests (e.g. housekeeping at a specific time; four hour rush laundry, etc.). Each request was happily received by the folks on the W/W line and each request was followed up by the W/W people to make sure it had been met to my satisfaction. I had only two occasions to interact with the folks downstairs but they were equally charming and friendly and helpful. Gone was all the attitude of before and the hip 20-somethings that know nothing about customer service. If you're like me and have previously written-off the W from past experience, I suggest you give it another try.<//Text>

Can't believe I now have to read all the fine print - I was charged $30 for packages! When I checked in they said nothing about the charge and I even tipped several dollars to the porter when he brought them to the front desk. He did offer to carry them to my room but I just carried them in one hand while I had my suitcase and computer in the other hand. That is how little we are talking about. Totally changed my perspective on how the services at SPG are changing - and even my Platinum status didn't get me a beak on the fees because they had already been charged to my credit card (which was where I first learned of the fee). PS - you can find the package handling listed in the fine print on the web site but would have to call the hotel to find out the outrageous amount (the delivery fees are lower than the hotels charge!!!)

I expect electric and water fees are not far behind.</Review>

< user_name>
mrbillone< /user_name>
<time>1399420800000< /time><Review>I've had the pleasure and privilege of staying in W Hotels since early in 2002. I've been to the San Francisco location three times and have spent over a dozen nights in Seattle. For whatever reason I remember my 2003 stay in SF to have been much nicer than our recent stay- May 2014.
All of my visits have been in a Fabulous King Corner room.
First I want to mention that I think Starwood has made a mistake pulling the small CD player from the rooms. In times past when entering the room the lighting would be set and the signature "W" CD playing. I loved it. Since sometime around 2006 that device has been pulled and one has to use the television/dvd combo to listen to the disc. Unfortunately that requires leaving the television on while listening. The light from the screen ruins the atmospheric ambience of the room as well effects the views. It's also a bit of a challenge finding the correct input setting with the remotes given. I'm fairly tech savvy, but it still took me a few minutes to complete the task. I made mention of this in Seattle. I was told to put a towel over the screen.
Our last stay was in room 2202. Upon entering the room I immediately noticed as to how dirty the windows were. Pretty bad. I never remember that being the case on any of my stays past. One of the windows also had a broken seal- dirty between panes.
A while later we found that housekeeping had apparently missed stocking the bathroom with bath towels. After contacting ~WW~ two towels were brought up to the room. I thought two was a little ridiculous being that almost every female I know uses two towels.
After coming back from diner, I decided to grab some time on the internet. I immediately found the $14.95/$19.95 daily charge. I mean really? I can understand paying for non essential items used in the room, but internet? My first thought was this will be my last stay at a Starwood property.
I had elected the "Green Service" which I thought meant that towels hanging up would stay and that the sheets wouldn't be changed. Later the next day I found that by selecting it we'd lost all services to the room. Not even the coffee was replenished. I immediately changed that mistake. I will say that after having the room serviced everything with exception to the windows was clean and in the order I was accustomed to. Note: Initially the room wasn't as clean as in times past. I also noticed that the towels provided were well worn and not at all plush.
On a positive note, the staff was very attentive and helpful.
Back to the internet, I might suggest if you feel it's necessary to charge, allow a basic 1.5 service free and charge for high-speed.</Review><rate>None<//rate><pics>None< /pics><gmap_id>0x8085807d77b62311:0x84055e3c40a911eb< /gmap_id><user>None<//user></record>

<Pictures>None<//Pictures><username>D7NYC< /username><review>To whom it may concern,

I am writing this to bring to your attention of my recent experience at the San Francisco W. I stayed five nights at room 2502, thanks to an upgrade offered to me. However, there's constantly some unidentifiable noise inside the bathroom. It wasn't bothering me in the beginning of my stay, but it was progressively worsened. I was too exhausted after work to bring this matter to management and ask for a different room.

Another thing that needs improvement is the card reader inside the elevator. My co-workers who stayed at W and I also experienced difficulties having our hotel cards scanned on a few occasions. I did notice other hotel guests were experiencing similar problem.

Besides the two issues as aforementioned, the hotel facilities and staffs were excellent. Kevin, the associate who assisted my check-in and check-out was friendly and helpful. He was very patient and offered his sincere apologies to me as I explained my room situation during check-out.

Being a SPG platinum member, I want the best experience for other travelers. But most importantly, I am hoping these issues will be addressed immediately.

CONS:
*   The AC was mediocre and didn't feel like it was properly cooling the room even at the lowest setting.
*   The TV is old and doesn't offer any connections for a Fire Stick/Roku - only had S-Video and Analog cable connections - no accessible HDMI on the TV.
*   Requires a $200 CC hold for amenities, which is the most I've ever seen held anywhere.

*   Mini fridge has no room for personal items, only pricey

PROS:
+   The decor was nice and had a modern feel, but it was made irrelevant by the numerous issues that need renovation.
+  The staff was very courteous and helpful.  They are what drove the 2 stars for this review.  If they were the only thing I was rating they would be 5 stars, but there was too many issues with the property itself.

<Pics>None<//Pics>< text>
I wanted to try another Starwood hotel so I decided to stay at the W. When we arrived the lobby was busy and the bar had a few people in it along with a DJ. It was around 8 or 9pm. The clerk greeted me and checked me into my 2 rooms. He said that I was a Platinum member and finished checking me in.

I then asked if there were any upgrades and he said that I was upgraded to a corner room with a view. It would have been nice to know that I had received an upgrade. He told me where the elevators were and we went to our rooms. He mentioned nothing else.

When we got to our rooms my wife asked about our breakfast comp and the clerk had not said anything about it. So I called the front desk and the clerk said that if I would come down he would have the voucher for me.

We went down to get the voucher and it was the same clerk that checked me in and he said that I had asked for the Starwood points earlier instead of the breakfast. I told him he never mentioned the choices at all and that I definitely do not need anymore points. He got us the vouchers one for each of my rooms.

I was very disappointed in the the lack of recognition a Platinum member held from this encounter which was my first, aside from the valet.

I became a Platinum member for elite service and your hotel doesn't seem to show any different service than another common guest.
The lobby had people in it yet I was the only one checking in at the time. There was another clerk doing nothing at another station maybe they might have been better, who knows.

Your hotel was nice and clean. We enjoyed the beds, very comfortable. The hotel look was trendy and had a nice atmosphere. But I am not sure if I would go there again since there are so many other choices to stay at. I hope you can improve on your customer service because that is what gets people back time and time again. thanks for your time.<//text>

<text>Beware of the 'complimentary' bike rentals. Bikes are not maintained and a flat tire left me stranded 4 miles from the hotel. Hotel staff did not appropriately or effectively respond to this issue.

Also there is extremely noisy construction going on next to the hotel - even on Saturday and Sunday starting around 8am. Hotel will claim that they have 'no control' over the noise. While this may be true, when one is seeking a weekend relaxation getaway, being awoken my jackhammers and drills at 8am on a Saturday and Sunday is not my idea of serenity. We booked using SPG luxury privilege and got upgraded to the fabulous room which was adorable but smaller than expected. The view was fantastic, though. Decor downstairs is nice, and we had drinks at the bar which tasted perfect ($16 cocktails). Had steak and eggs in Trace downstairs and thought they were well prepared. <userid>None< /userid><text>The W San Francisco is the place to be seen and heard, especially on weekends where throngs of business hippies converge at the bar to loud thumping music.

It can sometimes be too hip, and might not be the best option for families or guests who want a quiet night's rest. (I was woken up in succession for 2 nights by a rather drunk neighbor who kept on screaming at the top of her voice in the wee hours of the morning)

Room-wise, the room is a decent size, the bed is plush, and amenities are well-stocked with Bliss products. The gym is open till 1.30am daily which is a huge plus, and the hotel comes with a heated pool which is great for a few quick laps. Breakfast at Trace was quite an enjoyable experience, the blueberry pancakes were superb. There was the complimentary Azura transfer which really helped in sightseeing.

A couple of points which could have made the experience even better:

There is a $15 charge for in-room wifi which is rather exorbitant given most hotels at Union Square offer them on a complimentary basis. You can still get free wifi in the lobby, which can be ra a rather surreal experience when you are trying to reply to work emails amidst loud thumping music at the bar.

It seems to me that it is also bizarre why coffee making facilities need to be on a request basis, and that a $10 charge was levied for receiving a parcel. Most top hotels do not charge a penny for such a service.

Front desk service was also inconsistent. I met really helpful agents who were able to tell me the nearest Walgreens, and others who looked clueless when I asked for a breakdown in my hotel invoice.

I was also billed $5 for a W shopping tote after my trip, which to my chagrin, I had no idea what it even looked like. (I have since written to W and am pending a reply)

Overall, the experience has been pleasant, but perhaps a little too hip in some ways, when all you want at the end of a long day is a little TLC.<//text>< Name>
redmatryoshka</Name>

<Text>Everything about our stay was wonderful, the only problem we encountered was with The Style department. I am 10 weeks pregnant with twins, had been out of the hotel for 7 hours, and upon returning my room had still not been serviced. I felt very insulted when I spoke with the Style Manager Michael. He said I should have informed the hotel I was pregnant in order to get priority. He proceeded to give me excuses as to why it wasn't cleaned. Ouch. I don't want excuses, I want genuine empathy. Offering me a late check out was hardly even an offer, it felt forced. Plus we were leaving early in the morning. Call me crazy, but as someone who worked in management for Starwood in the past, 7 hours on a Saturday should be plenty of time to get your room services. If you know you are fully committed, hire more people to get the job done. I shouldn't need priority just because I'm pregnant. I felt like he didn't care, especially because he didn't try to correctly pronounce my last name. <user>104825892615223797066< /user>< user_name>
Jessica Neagle<//user_name>
< Review>
Fun and swanky hotel! From the hip interior design to the many beautiful details, like fresh fruit in the lobby and gym to the beautiful florals in the elevator lobby, this is a well appointed place to stay and perfectly suits the vibe of San Francisco. Everyone I encountered was friendly and helpful, great customer service. Loved the room. Really comfortable bed and the little window seats made my heart happy. The location is amazing -SF Museum of Moden Art is next door Moscone Center a block away and Yerba Buena Gardens across the street. Anything else you want to visit is just a short streetcar or timeshare away, but there is more than enough in walking distance! Came for the Labor Day weekend and would love to stay here again soon.< /Review>

< Text>
The hotel environment in terms of room, atmosphere etc. was outstanding. The location, for us, was excellent. On the earlier leg of our journey we stayed in the Fisherman's Wharf area and this was much better placed in terms of seeing and experiencing the city. Two (hopefully minor) niggles, however, remove the fifth star. First, a couple of wrong bits of information given were unhelpful: one by the reception desk over the phone about times for breakfast on Easter morning - this ended up changing our plans for the morning which was disappointing. It was also disappointing to our 7 year old and myself that the pool the TV-based hotel info claimed was available has now closed. Second, we have had a strange experience with credit card charges. Having booked a second night ourselves and prepaid the first with our travel agent, we discovered that there are over $1700 in charges pending on our card in separate transactions. We queried this in alarm with the front desk, to be reassured that they will all drop off and are a 'quirk' of the system to do with 'authorisations'. This seems to us a pretty massive quirk, however, given the total charges for the extra night should amount to around $250. We leave this morning and it seems unlikely this will be resolved until we get home so are having to trust the reputation of the hotel on this one rather more than we'd like as the charges will apparently 'drop off'. Weird, and a rather alarming end to an otherwise very enjoyable stay.<//Text>

< text>
I had a very bad experience at this hotel. I arrived and was told I could be placed in a room on the very top floor, but it wouldn't have a king bed like I had reserved, it would have two beds instead. I don't mind two queens, so I said alright. When I arrived in my room I found instead one tiny bed---not even full-sized. It was also an accessible room, but other than a different bathroom that seemed okay. I was tired so I decided I'd try it for a night and deal with it the next day if it was an issue. I was woken up around 1:30 in the morning by people in the next room talking. They were talking at normal voice, but there was a connecting door that had NO sound insulation. I had to wait until they went to bed in order to get back to sleep. In the morning I rushed off to work and asked at the front desk for a new room when I returned in the evening. The receptionist said there was nothing she could do, but that a new person was in the next room so it would probably be quieter. I explained that I had reserved a king room so it was a bit ridiculous that there was nothing she could do, but she just shrugged, said sorry, and said I could call down with a noise complaint after 10pm if it became a problem. I ended up just having to listen to the man in the next room talk on the phone with his wife--it was before 10pm, but honestly I would have felt uncomfortable calling in with a noise complaint when the man was just having a normal conversation. This hotel should fix it's sound issues for connecting rooms, not give people tiny beds when they asked for kings, and have some way to address people's complaints when they come up, especially if they have not been given the room type they reserved. Especially as a loyal spg customer this experience was unexpected and terrible. I will not plan to return to this hotel.< /text>

< Text>
of all the starwood properties i've stayed at in the us and internationally, the W at SF was one of the most disappointing. lack of customer service, lack of spg recognition, multiple phone calls and follow ups on requests and questions on my part (the opposite of their "whatever, whenever" motto. addressing me by the wrong name multiple times during my stay-- had to correct multiple times (they should have just kept it to Ms. if the staff weren't sure). window panels in the room were peeled off and hanging on a hinge but covered by the curtain. lack of door for the bathroom (not ideal when sharing room with someone else). lack of responsiveness from housekeeping for restocking throughout the day (yes, had to request multiple times before housekeeping came). no suite at this hotel w/ 2 beds. no executive lounge. even though they advertise the acura service, they were completely unavailable during the week we stayed at the property. also never returned my voicemail... had to call them back on my own.

the breakfast at trace was delicious.

i am purposely staying at another W in my recent trip to NYC to see if the unhelpful and pretentious staff is a trend at the W or if it's just exclusive to SF.<//Text>

< UserId.>
None< /UserId.>
<username>SurfUS</username><date>1476748800000< /date><Rating>None</Rating>< Text>
I'm reviewing this based on SPG hotel stays in general and not stays at the W. From the view of a normal SPG member

Upon arriving to the hotel and waiting in line to check-in, I was told that they would have to find the person who checks in SPG members. Which only took a few extra minutes, however it was odd. I was checking in around 6pm during the week and the checkin area was packed with overflow from the bar/club. So it made the process quite annoying. 

Once I found my way up to the room, I noticed a nicely laid out room with the expected cheesy design for a W hotel. When I went to take a shower, I pulled to toggle to have all the water go through the shower head, however there was still quite a bit of water still coming out of the tub valve and only a small bit coming out of the shower head. Annoying, but I didn't have time to call the desk for a fix. When I left for the next morning I mentioned it however upon returning there was no fix for the second night. 

When returning for the second night around 10pm after a days work, the bar/club overflow was way beyond expected. Even filled into the elevator hallway with bar guests riding around the elevators. 

All in All, I believe they need to step up their Hotel presence and hotel guest services on the main floor and segment the bar/club from checkin and guest access. I like being in the action and dont mind going to the party. I just dont want to have to deal with it just to get to my room, checkin/checkout, and do basic hotel things. Maybe a full wall between the club and the hotel checkin will help both organize the staff and segment non-guests from hotel processes.</Text>

<Gmap_id>0x8085807d77b62311:0x84055e3c40a911eb< /Gmap_id></record>
</dataset><record>
< rating>
3< /rating>
< review>
W hotels are always hit or miss. They tend to be a bit flashy and cater to a younger 'hipper' crowd. This particular W, has some interesting styling as you enter, however feels a bit cluttered given the smaller size of the lobby and bar. The rooms are pretty nice, with very modern amenities, and that's what counts.

As an SPG Platinum member, I was offered a room upgrade, and the other standard platinum amenities.

One of the most memorable things from my stay was the awesome 3D hologram effect on the back elevator wall. I almost missed my floor staring at it.

The hotel is a short walk from most major attractions, but might require a cab to hit some of the best spots. Overall I was pleased with my stay, but will try another SPG property when I'm in SF.</review>

< Rate>

< review>
Everything from valet parking to check-out was handled so smoothly. The entire staff I encountered treated me like I was someone special, from the valet to room service. We were given a room on the 30th floor with a spectacular view of the Bay Bridge. Whatever Whenever truly means whatever whenever -- I needed a razor, bam! We opted for a "green" stay, but when I requested more towels, bam! The bartender did not make me feel awkward or uncomfortable when I cashed in my drink coupons that came with the parking package I signed up for. My only disappointment came with the pool/spa..I was excited about an indoor pool, hoping to do some laps, but it was freezing. As was the entire pool area. It was also freezing in the spa, and no one seemed to know how to work the amenities, such as the steam room or sauna..the only place to get warmth was if you used the blow dryer..this made me especially sad, because I treated my friend to a very expensive treatment, and she was not able to enjoy fully because of the cold. Expected more from a Bliss spa. Also didn't appreciate the pushing of products at the spa. Too "salesy" ...I loved the proximity of the hotel to all things fun-- we walked over to Metreon to see movies and grab a quick bite. Peet's Coffee was fabulous right down 3rd Street, and we cable-carred back from Fisherman's Wharf to Powell and Market, and had a short walk back to hotel.
Overall, I LOVE this hotel and would stay there again. And again.< /review>

<review>I am extremely disappointed in my experience with the W Hotel San Francisco. I booked the Cirque du Soleil package that included tickets to a show, complementary parking and cocktails for one night stay.
The receptionist was very cold. No kind of greeting no acknowledgement of the package nothing. I thought it strange but wrote it off as an inexperienced staff. The room was as expected, nothing spectacular but nothing to complain about. It was clean, pretty comfortable with a nice view.

Since the receptionist did not mentioned anything about tickets I was expecting to find them in my room. Nothing...

When I called the front desk to inquire about my show tickets I find a flabbergasted employee explaining that she will need to contact her manager and get back to me. This was the first but not last time I had to reach for the phone.

The manager called back after 5 minutes asking me what day I want to go to the show. How about tonight I answer while I am staying in your hotel? He then says he will need to purchase tickets and will call me back when done. The show was for 8PM and I was on the phone from 5:00 to 6PM trying to sort out my ticket situation.

The manager buys the tickets and copies me on the purchase thinking that the order receipt would be sufficient to get me in. Good thing I read the fine print and find out that the tickets need to be presented in printed format with a bar code. Meanwhile someone comes to my door to give my a hard copy of the mostly useless ticket receipt.

Picked up the phone again to request a printout of the tickets prior to our booked dinner reservation which was on our way to the show. As I walk up to the desk and ask for my tickets, I get carded instead of receiving an apology for making me work for something that was supposed to be part of the package. Can they be any ruder?

Unfortunately this wasn't the only mishap. The seats to the show were in the second to last row with the action bearably visible and when checking out W Hotel charged me for more than they should have and only promised to take care of it (within a week) after I pointed it out. The receptionist tried to explain (lie) to me that the overcharge was a security deposit that will be reimbursed, instead of apologizing for their mistake. Really? Do you train your people to insult your guests?

Needless to say, I don't intend to stay there ever again and I'll make sure the Fortune 500 company I work for won't consider the SF location either.</review>< Resp>

< text>
My favorite hotel in SF. The rooms are not huge but are nicely updated and very modern. Internet is decent speed, good enough to get work done and use video or voice chat. Staff at the W are always amazing and they really go the extra mile to make guests happy.

The hotel is located right across from Moscone Center and the Yerba Buena gardens. Easy to walk to just about anything nearby. Starbucks is across the street for those of us that are hooked on caffeine or coffee.</text>

<user>None< /user>< Name>
vanariesboy</Name>
< Time>
1384646400000<//Time>
<rate>None</rate><text>We stayed five nights at the W San Francisco while on vacation in late July 2013. This hotel is conveniently located in SOMA, about two blocks south of Market Street. Access from the airport is easy by BART to the Montgomery Street station.

The W has a reputation for a busy lobby with loud music playing. This is well-deserved: the lobby was hopping most of the time we were there. It wasn‚Äôt disruptive to our stay, though: none of the music carried up to our floor (the 20th) and, in fact, the room was very quiet and we never heard sound from the hallway or the adjacent rooms.

Despite being an SPG Platinum member, the hotel offered only a one-level upgrade, from a ‚ÄúWonderful‚Äù to a ‚ÄúSpectacular‚Äù room ‚Äì this was still the most basic room at this hotel, but on a higher floor. The room was very cutely decorated, with little knick-nacks all over the place, including a light-up, colour-changing Buddha. In addition to a fully stocked minibar, there was a bottle of wine and several bottles of hard alcohol placed around the desk area. On a more practical note, there was a nifty device on the desk capable of charging numerous brands of cell phones, as well as five other plugs at desk level for computers or other devices. The ‚Äòlittle things‚Äô were done nicely, like a light in the closet that turns on automatically when you open the door. There was also a cozy window seat with a nice view of the Bay Bridge.

The bathroom was bright and clean. The ‚ÄúBliss‚Äù bath amenities, especially the lemon-scented soap, face wash, and body butter cream, were delightful as always.

The best feature of the room, however, was the bed. We had a king-size pillow-top bed with just the right combination of support and softness. We slept soundly every night of our stay.

The room did not come equipped with a coffee maker, but the hotel will provide a Keurig machine at no charge upon request. However, the coffee and condiments are not refreshed daily by housekeeping; you need to call and ask. The Whatever/Whenever service is always attentive, though.

Unique among Starwood hotels, the W chain has an iPhone app that, among other things, allows guests to make requests, order room service, etc., without having to pick up the phone. Unfortunately at the W San Francisco the app didn‚Äôt work properly, and produced a ‚Äòserver error‚Äô at the very final stage of ordering. No worries, though: the ‚ÄúWhatever/Whenever‚Äù service always picked up the phone immediately, addressed me by name, and were happy to meet any request. Overall, we found the level of service by hotel staff to be among the best we‚Äôd ever received in a hotel.

The fitness centre is located in a nice, bright area on the fourth floor. There is a shallow swimming pool and a hot tub, both located under a large skylight. The pool area is open until midnight, which is a major plus because it allows evening time in the hot tub after families and small children have gone to bed.

The fitness centre itself has a good number of up-to-date cardio machines, but is really lacking in the strength department. There is really no available floor space for stretching, and has only one rack of free weights and one multi-purpose weight/pulley machine. The biggest problem, however, surrounds the cardio equipment: the ceiling is too low, and as a 6‚Äô3‚Äù person I hit my head several times while using the elliptical and treadmill. This safety concern must be remedied as soon as possible.

We ate breakfast each morning in the hotel restaurant, Trace. There is no buffet but the menu offers a reasonable selection. The items were tasty with generous portion sizes. At this hotel, the SPG Platinum breakfast benefit is a $15 credit per person, which will cover about half the items on the menu. It does *not* cover the absurdly high $5.50 cost of coffee, however. In fact, the very same coffee is available for free each morning a few paces away in the bar.

A unique feature of W Hotels is the ‚ÄúAcura Experience‚Äù car service. Despite the text in the hotel‚Äôs guest directory, the service is in fact only available afternoons. We used it to go to an out-of-the-way museum, and both the car and driver were very pleasant; the driver even suggested other destinations in the same area. There is an on-board video touting the Acura‚Äôs features, but the sales pitch was low-key and a small price to pay for this complimentary service.

Overall, we were very impressed with our stay at the W San Francisco. Without exception, the staff were attentive and friendly. Even our basic room was quiet, comfortable, and restful. We will definitely stay here again.

Tip: take the time to explore your room. The nooks and crannies are packed with small delights.<//text><Pics>None</Pics><Resp>None</Resp>< gmapID>

< user_name>
Asa Perry<//user_name>
< date>
1426565003228</date>
< Rating>
2<//Rating>
<text>I booked a prepaid rate in February, and upon check in I learned there was a cheaper rate but was not able to take advantage of the rate.  I was told the rate I prepaid was a "very good rate", and that I had been upgraded to a corner room.  Okay, if the rate I paid was more expensive than the current rate on day of check in, obviously my rate is not a "very good rate", and being upgraded comes with Platinum status of upgrade rooms are available.  Not quite sure how either of the hotel staff reasonings were valid.

Upon check in, everyone was friendly and I had no issues with the front desk staff.

Once in my room, I noticed the following which in my opinion are unacceptable and show a lack of attention to detail.  No cushion or pillows on the couch, what appeared to be toothpaste smeared in the bathroom water glasses, and the flat sheet used to cover the mattress was too small for the king size bed (I am thinking a queen size flat sheet was used).  I contacted the front desk and they did bring up a cushion for the couch, replaced the water glasses in the room, and placed an appropriate size flat sheet overtop the mattress.

The next night, my partner and I decided to grab a sandwich and sit on the couch to eat prior to going out.  We noticed what appeared to be dried vomit on the couch near the wall closer to the floor.  I informed the front desk once again, and upon our return to the room I received a telephone message from the housekeeping manager letting me know he personally inspected the room and did not find any vomit on the wall by the couch.  Clearly they got the placement of the vomit incorrect and if the manager truly did inspect the wall I would have hoped he would have seen the vomit on the couch too.  It concerns me his attention to detail is not up to par.

Lastly, there was a feather on the floor outside our room which was not there upon check in but was there after the first instance occurred.  Keep in mind the housekeeping manager came to the room to inspect the vomit situation and the feather was still on the floor outside our room.  I would have expected the manager of all people the notice this detail and pick up the feather.  The carpeting was a dark blue I believe and the feather was white.  Not hard to miss in my opinion.

One thing I did not bother to inform the front desk about was the state of the window sills behind the shutters.  I do not believe the sills have ever been cleaned.  The amount of dust and dirt was repulsive, and I would hope this detail would not be overlooked.

I would not recommend this hotel, and do not plan on staying at this property again.  As a matter of fact I planned to stay at the W in Hollywood later in the week and have since cancelled that reservation because of my first W experience in San Francisco.

I hope others have a better experience or find this review helpful.< /text><pics>None</pics><Response>None< /Response><Gmap_id>0x8085807d77b62311:0x84055e3c40a911eb</Gmap_id></record></dataset><record>
